Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, US – No policy pits good economics so squarely against good politics as do food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies have become a central issue for three of the world’s most important new leaders: Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi faces a subsidy reduction that is better than anticipated.
Modi, on the other hand, faces a much worse situation, even threatening to derail the long-awaited WTO agreement.
And Widodo's situation remains unclear.
In July, Xi Xi completed a feat that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East could achieve: he substantially reduced long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Surprisingly, there were almost no protest demonstrations.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and is urgently in need of reform.
Bread prices have remained at extremely low levels, often used for animal feed.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often triggered unrest, even toppling governments.
But the Sissi government seems to be making progress on this front as well.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sissi had no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the budget deficit target for the next fiscal year is 10% of GDP (it would be 14% without the subsidy cuts).
But hardly anyone expected Xi to be more proactive than Modi, who ascended to the prime ministership in a India eager for thorough economic reforms through an overwhelming democratic majority.
In Indonesia, Joko Widodo, who took office in October, inherits fuel subsidies worth $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), which have already become a heavy burden on the nation.
Susilo, who stepped down, had taken a courageous first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Widodo’s advisers recommend cutting the remaining subsidies, and he candidly announced plans to phase them out over four years.
Economists are confident in opposing commodity subsidies, as agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition with many consumers on the demand side and many producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive markets, it is government — not large private monopolies — that is the problem.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
The sharp debates over food and fossil fuel subsidies stem from their frequent invocation of environmental or egalitarian rhetoric, which often fails to achieve those goals, and can even exacerbate them.
Only about 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies enrich the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest.
Worldwide, only far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy; the Modi government, which aimed to protect agricultural subsidies, is a case in point.
In fact, the Modi government vetoed the World Trade Organization compromise that would have destroyed the most significant multilateral trade negotiation progress over the past decade.
&lt;span&gt;Subsidies for agriculture sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; and sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in rich countries.&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;s&gt;India's policies aim to do both.&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;s&gt;As a result, India has achieved something remarkable: it provides consumers with wheat at artificially low prices while experiencing overproduction because farmers can get high prices.&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;s&gt;(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs – electricity, water, and fertilizers – which leads to environmental damage.&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;s&gt;The government acquires large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, and the distribution to consumers is both corrupt and fails to serve the goal of helping the poor.&lt;/s&gt;
Government may continue to maintain subsidies and storage reserves.
But it knows that this would violate WTO rules.
Since they cannot permanently change these rules, Modi simply rejected the Trade Facilitation Agreement (TFA) that the WTO was eagerly awaiting.
Once subsidies are implemented, it's hard to withdraw them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did in the last decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from shocks.
But people accustomed to official food and energy prices would demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong reason why subsidies should not have been implemented in the first place.
That does not mean, however, that maintaining subsidies once they are implemented would always be the wisest choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price hikes is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could also erupt.
Similarly, if the widening gap ultimately leads to higher retail prices, slow-moving leaders would also not benefit.
In an ideal scenario, while cutting food and energy subsidies, other more effective measures to support low-income households should also be taken.
Developing countries have already learned much about effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família conditional cash transfer programs, as well as innovative technological advancements like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries may only be forced to adjust their budgets when crises hit, leaving them without money for transfers that would alleviate pain.
Clever politicians might implement unpopular adjustments at the outset of their terms.
Joko Widodo and Xi Xi both followed this approach.
And Modi, who won the election by campaigning on the slogan of market reforms, is now lagging behind.
